\begin_layout Subsection
Wednesday
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Continued fine reading of chapter 5 from Aharnov's book.
 It has started to make some sense finally.
 Although I am still not clear about the doubts from last time, the new
 sections (with the modifications such as 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 as opposed to 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ipL/\hbar}$
\end_inset

) have started making sense.
 I also seem to have found a flaw in one of the calculations, where it is
 shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ipL/\hbar}f(x)=f(x+L)$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 The important point I learnt this time however, was the following statement:
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mod}$
\end_inset

 (defined always with 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 at the back of the mind) is completely uncertain iff (if and only if) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e^{in\hat{p}L/\hbar}\right\rangle =0\,\forall\, n\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If one thinks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 as a number, and the expectation as these numbers occurring with classical
 probabilities, then one can easily prove this.
 In any case, if taken as a definition also (because it is rather sensible:
 it is possible that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{p}\right\rangle \neq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\lang english

\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e^{in\hat{p}L/\hbar}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
