\begin_layout Subsection
Monday, May 25
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Essentially spent time reading the NJP paper by Aharnov et al
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It starts by building on the idea of what changes when we do a which way
 measurement (WWM), in the context of a double slit experiment
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Talks about debates over momentum changes before and after, claims some
 results about how to measure them and so on
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Discusses basic strategies of measurement, the moments and the fourier transform
 approach, justifies how the latter is better
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Talks about modular variables (this is essentially the same as that in the
 book) except that he discusses 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How the parity operator may be used to yield the value of the local phase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Explains conservation of modular momentum slightly better than it is done
 in the book (basically using the Heisenberg picture and time evolution
 etc.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Explains the consequence of a WWM on the modular variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Justifies why it is impossible to measure these non local interactions
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Discusses how indeed the non local effect may be observed using weak measurement
s
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
<This I didn't read completely, however I read about weak measurements from
 this link [http://quanta.ws/ojs/index.php/quanta/article/view/14] till page
 5 or so>
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Weak measurements are based on the idea that the quantum system is coupled
 to a measurement device, which is itself quantum mechanical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The usual projective measurements are done on the measurement device (which
 is quantum) after letting it interact with the quantum system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The outcomes then are used to determine properties of the quantum system,
 with disturbance which can be made arbitrarily small
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then there're more advanced methods where you pre and post select etc.
 which I haven't fully read about
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Apparently, weak values have interpretation which is not yet fully accepted
 and I was advised not to pursue this just yet.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Tuesday, May 26
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Roope's Lecture(s)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Roope today discussed how to generalize evolution of states, following a
 similar minimalistic assumption approach
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
He defined Channels and Operations (based on whether they preserve the trace
 or decrease it) as maps from 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\mathcal{H})\to T(\mathcal{H})^{+}$
\end_inset

 (meaning from the space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

s to that where the trace can be 
\begin_inset Formula $\le1$
\end_inset

 but must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\ge0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He put various constraints on the map and added an extra assumption about
 complete positivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He then discussed the Schrodinger and Heisenberg picture in the context
 of these operators.
 The statement is basically that we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}=\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the dual space of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (in finite dimensions, apparently they're same).
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\, N:T\to T,\,\exists\, N^{*}:\mathcal{L}\to\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 which is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $tr[N(T)E]=tr[TN^{*}(E)]$
\end_inset

.
 Afterwards, during the exercise session, he derived various results using
 just this statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then he went on to describe Steinspring's dialation thm, which is essentially
 a statement about how to characterise the most general `evolution' of a
 quantum system, in terms of a unitary.
 The claim is that for a given channel 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon:T\to T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\,(\mathcal{H}_{E},\xi,U):\epsilon(\rho)=tr_{E}(U(\rho\otimes\xi)U^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 which is saying that the channel is just a unitary evolution of the state
 in a larger space, which is later traced out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, he went on to talking about the Kraus Decomposition, which characterize
s a channel by giving an explicit decomposition.
 [I'm skipping the details now]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And in the end, he described a way for testing/characterising Completely
 Positive maps.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
There're various things he did (TODO: complete this section)
\end_layout

