\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Building on post discussion with Otfried, the idea was to understand better
 why while the moments are phase independent, how 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 was phase dependent (phase similar to the one in the previous context,
 further assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are not overlapping, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=\psi_{1}+e^{i\phi}\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 The idea basically is that, 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
the assumption, as stated above forces us to consider non analytic functions
 only, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\ne\sum\frac{f^{n}(0)x^{n}}{n!}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Essentially you're saying that you can't find a convergent sequence for
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 around some point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nexists\, a_{n}\, s.t.\, f(x)=a_{0}+a_{1}(x-x_{0})+a_{2}(x-x_{0})^{2}+\dots$
\end_inset

 which essentially means that the taylor expansion doesn't exist for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Easiest example is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 is non analytic, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x+x_{0})$
\end_inset

 is also non analytic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 as the generator of infinitesimal translations, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\frac{i\hat{p}\delta L}{\hbar})\psi(x)=\psi(x+\delta L)$
\end_inset

.
 If I put 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L=L/N$
\end_inset

, and apply this operation 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 times, s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, then I can write 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar N})^{N}\psi(x)=e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}\psi(x+L)$
\end_inset

.
 For this, I didn't have to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 is analytic.
 Call this definition 1.
 (TODO: Prove this)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If I assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 is analytic, I can write 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}\psi(x)=\left[1+\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}+\frac{1}{2!}\left(\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}\right)^{2}+\dots\right]\psi(x)=\frac{i}{\hbar}\sum\frac{\psi^{n}(x)L^{n}}{n!}=\psi(x+L)$
\end_inset

, which is perfectly valid.
 However, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 is not analytic, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x+L)\ne\frac{i}{\hbar}\sum\frac{\psi^{n}(x)L^{n}}{n!}$
\end_inset

.
 Yet, by definition 1, the RHS can be obtained even for non analytic functions.
 I call this definition 2: 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}=\left[1+\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}+\frac{1}{2!}\left(\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}\right)^{2}+\dots\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conclusion: Since 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(a) the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}$
\end_inset

 by definition 1 holds for non analytic functions and
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(b) an operator is defined by it's action on its domain, 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

it is safe to conclude that when extended to the domain of non analytic
 functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}}\ne\left[1+\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}+\frac{1}{2!}\left(\frac{i\hat{p}L}{\hbar}\right)^{2}+\dots\right]$
\end_inset

, viz.
 definition 2 doesn't always hold.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
He suggested I read the paper by Aharnov on using modular variables in the
 Aharnov Bohm effect to explain when it happens
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some of the ideas that came up include
\end_layout

