\begin_layout Itemize
I watched this seminar (according to what I'd decided yesterday) titled
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Phase Factors, Gauge Theories and Strings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and in this, the person systematically discussed the origin of potentials
 and gauges and their physicality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The most interesting aspect was Maxwell's justification for introducing
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 field.
 He was unhappy by the 
\emph on
non-locality
\emph default
 of the faraday induction law.
 To make this effect local, he introduced 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 And so this non locality (if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not accepted as physical) goes back all the way to classical electrodynamics.
 This makes it harder to understand the precise meaning of non-locality
 in quantum mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There was also this interesting aspect about how Dirac had predicted that
 the electromagnetic charge must be quantized, if there exist magnetic monopoles
 that we can't detect.
 Infact AB is a non-trivial example of where Dirac's approach proves 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 field has physical significance and observable effect.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
