\begin_layout Itemize
Chapter 4 notes
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is from Aharnov's book.
 I started writing the full notes, and realized that only the kinematic
 momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=p=P-\frac{e}{c}A$
\end_inset

 is infact gauge invariant because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\psi^{*}\pi\psi=\int\psi^{*}(P-\frac{e}{c}A)\psi=\int\psi'^{*}(P-\frac{e}{c}A')\psi'
\]

\end_inset

 infact, now that I think of it, it is essentially just 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mu}\psi\to D_{\mu}\psi$
\end_inset

 so that when 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\to\psi'$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\mu}\psi\to e^{i\lambda}D_{\mu}\psi$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\psi^{*}D_{\mu}\psi\to\int\psi'^{*}D'_{\mu}\psi'=\int e^{-i\lambda}\psi^{*}e^{i\lambda}D_{\mu}\psi=\int\psi^{*}D_{\mu}\psi
\]

\end_inset

So that means that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the kinematic momentum (even in QFT, man I'm an idiot, didn't
 see it then) .
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 however is not gauge invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I also had some doubts about how Newton's law wasn't holding.
 The electron is pulling/pushing the plates together, but there's no force
 being applied on it.
 I mean if I consider this situation classically also, no double slit, just
 an electron passing by a capacitor, mustn't Newton's law hold?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It's not complete yet, the next section I still have to write.
\end_layout

