\begin_layout Itemize
It was almost trivial to see how an atom can be used to create the phase
 we wanted.
 The issue is however that this is not an effect of adding a step potential
 to the photons.
 The effect is similar to adding a step potential.
 So this is not a genuine AB effect setup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To construct a setup where this emerges, it was concluded that since from
 
\begin_inset Formula $L=F^{2}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $H\propto E^{2}+B^{2}$
\end_inset

, which has no freedom whatsoever, therefore we must include interactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For the fermion in classical field, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\frac{1}{2m}(P-eA)^{2}+eV$
\end_inset

 which arises from 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{p}+L_{fp}$
\end_inset

, we must have analogously therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}+L_{fp}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the kind of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 that we really need.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This can be justified further by arguments such as `given the field configuratio
n, find the motion of the particle' requires us keep the 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}$
\end_inset

 fixed, therefore it doesn't contribute to the dynamics.
 Similarly, we must `keep the charges and currents fixed, and find field
 equations'.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, one must realize that 
\begin_inset Formula $H=p.v-L$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 must include even parts that're not varied.
 This I have to figure out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assuming though that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{f}+L_{fp}$
\end_inset

 are enough, I must obtain the relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and see what kind of charge configuration I can use to construct a step
 like potential.
 So this has two steps
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Construct 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and find the appropriate charge distribution | one intuitive possibility
 is to use two cavities and place a capacitor in between them
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the intuitive possibility has merit (and this was anyway motivated by
 being closer to the classical result), 
\end_layout

