\begin_layout Itemize
Continuous variable bell test
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So basically in the bell test, there're Alice's measurements, which are
 along 
\begin_inset Formula $z,\, x$
\end_inset

 and then there're Bob's measurements which are along 
\begin_inset Formula $z',\, x'$
\end_inset

.
 The state is 
\begin_inset Formula $01-10$
\end_inset

 normalized, and then the result is that the inequality is violated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I wanted to convert this into a setting where only one particular observable
 is measured, say 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (I'm obviously talking about spins, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

).
 The question then was if I could find suitable unitaries such that the
 effectively, when I calculate the expectations, I get the same answer.
 The answer I found is yes (rather trivially if thought of geomtrically).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Next I asked if I could make those unitaries act like essentially only adjusting
 the phases of the state.
 I figured that can also be done.
 Instead of measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and using 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\sigma_{y}\theta/2}$
\end_inset

 (with various 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 yielding essentially various measurement settings) I could measure along
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and apply 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\sigma_{z}\theta/2}$
\end_inset

.
 This way then, the working of the unitary is infact just the phase shift
 I can happily do with my continuous variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Why this was useless? Well, it is deceptively close.
 It is not actually that simple, because now the simple phase shifts happen
 if the state is written in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 basis, however I am measuring along the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 basis.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
