\begin_layout Itemize
Continuous Variable Bell Test
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Ali told me about the more elegant representation he'd found for his contextuali
ty paper with the set 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{i})$
\end_inset

 forming the pauli matrices.
 He showed that the commutation is obeyed if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy a constraint.
 The task was to use this formalism and arrive at the violation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To that end, I started looking for states that correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\pm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 etc.
 and realized after an entire day of thinking, that it is not straight forward,
 and perhaps, if one of my assumptions isn't false (that there're only two
 eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 upto phase/scaling ofcourse) then these states don't span, well anything.
 You can't even construct eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{2})$
\end_inset

 from those of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I had spent the whole day thinking about things based on the wrong assumption
 that displacement operators only displace.
 They infact, also add a phase which prevents say 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}\left|n\alpha+\beta\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 from being an eigenstate of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
My usual scheme of using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0/1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 states with 
\begin_inset Formula $2L$
\end_inset

 separated lumps also doesn't work if the lumps are made of coherent states.
 Other than it not being an eigenstate of neither 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{1})$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{2})$
\end_inset

, they are not even orthogonal.
 I had infact imagined that states of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m,n}\left|n\alpha_{1}+m\alpha_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are simultaneous eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\alpha_{2})$
\end_inset

 while these operators don't even commute.
 Now I am in a situation where I can't even construct eigenkets general
 enough to span another eigenket!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Other than this, I added the operator for the phases, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

's analogue in the continuous variable case.
\end_layout

