\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Read the GHZ paper further, realized that they were using more fancy things
 than just modular operators.
 They were using some kind of binary operators.
 Idea was that eventually, they'll construct an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $[\tilde{x}]_{k}$
\end_inset

 which would essentially yield the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th bit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 when acted upon 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 They then exponentiate such operators and define 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=iXY$
\end_inset

 (I actually never realized that you could easily define 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}\propto i\sigma_{x}\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $[\sigma_{x},\sigma_{y}]=2i\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\sigma_{x},\sigma_{y}\}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The point is that when we ask for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{modL}$
\end_inset

 say, then we extract infinite bits, but they're not really needed.
 For instance my 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(x_{mod2L})$
\end_inset

 operator essentially only needs to know if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{mod}<L$
\end_inset

 or not.
 So my 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 operator is infact somehow only using 1 bit of information.
 This is perhaps the right direction towards an elegant generalization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I found that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 works even when 
\begin_inset Formula $X'\equiv\left(X+X^{\dagger}\right)/2$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X'\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 To check if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 also work,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I need to figure how to convert (the old problem which I didn't solve then
 because it seemed like a digression) between position ket representation
 and momentum ket representation (I mean I know how, but I just don't get
 the right result), since I can't use the displacement action as I could
 with usual modular variables.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

