\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So I could start with field quantization for the E, B fields.
 In that case, the 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 field is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 field is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 However, this is when they quantize in a box.
 When they quantize in general, then they have 
\begin_inset Formula $q+ip=A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q-ip=A^{*}$
\end_inset

 and then it takes more reading to understand how they all relate to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, the observable.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I also just started thinking, agreed that the Hamiltonian is the same as
 that for a harmonic oscillator.
 That doesn't mean that the time evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $q,\, p$
\end_inset

 should be given by the Heisenberg equation of motion, or does it? Well
 if the Hamiltonian is correct, then given the right coordinates (q and
 p as we have), it should give the right evolution equations when plugged
 into the Hamilton's equations.
 So yes, in general also, one writes a Hamiltonian first which gives the
 right dynamics and then quantizes the conjugate variables.
 The usual trick.
 (I wonder at times if you could do anything other than the Lagrangian or
 the Hamiltonian, but not now anyway).
 Mandy had explained the rest quite well, about what picture is associated
 with the quantum states and where it's happening in the physical space.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The other approach is that I take a wavefunction as I had, and then just
 evolve it according to a free Hamiltonian and from the interference obtained
 (from 
\begin_inset Formula $|\left\langle x|\psi\right\rangle |^{2}$
\end_inset

) I can explore how to extract 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mod2L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I remember now the contradiction.
 The claim was that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(t)^{*}p^{k}q^{m}\psi(t)$
\end_inset

 doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle +e^{i\phi}\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 don't overlap to start with, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is freely evolved, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H=p^{2}/2m$
\end_inset

.
 The contradiction is based on intuition.
 It is known that under free evolution, the wavefunction diffuses.
 So the two lumps should eventually overlap.
 If they do overlap, I expect ...
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Allright, after all this mumbo jumbo and confusion, I just realized that
 I must not try to find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,\,\theta$
\end_inset

 and take them as given.
 The point is that I should just choose between 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1},\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 (say) and then measure 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 somehow.
 This must yield a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\le X\le1$
\end_inset

.
 Now I share my values with Alice and we plug them in the Bell's inequality
 and let the experiments say whether or not there's a violation.
 The question really now is how to find the measurement outcome of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 I got all confused.
 So for any observable, the axiom is that the outcome must be one of the
 eigenvalues, corresponding to the eigenket to which the state is collapsed.
 The issue is that my eigenkets are not really complete, or atleast not
 the `subspace' (subset, fine) I am considering.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\pm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are not really eigenkets and that's why all the hassle.
 If they were, then the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 would be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 But here that's not the case; 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 must come into the picture somehow.
 Is it possible to have observables who's eigenkets aren't complete? That
 way I have difficulty figuring how to measure even theoretically.
 Maybe the notion of measurement can be generalized in some way here (I
 must get the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

s as probabilities somehow).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the way back, I figured that if I use unnormalized eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle \equiv\sum_{n}\left|x=\tilde{x}+nL\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{L}d\tilde{x}\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle \left\langle \tilde{x}\right|=1$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{L}d\tilde{x}\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle \left\langle \tilde{x}\right|\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x\right\rangle ,\,\forall\, x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 However, only now I realized that such states would give 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle =\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which means the measurement will always yield 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 What about the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle \equiv\sum_{n}(-1)^{n}\left|x=\tilde{x}+nL\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 type of states? These are the ones that were supposed to yield 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =-\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 resulting in a 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 outcome.
 
\end_layout

