\begin_layout Itemize
Paradox?: So the measurement axiom seems to suggest we express our state
 in terms of eigenstates of the operator corresponding to the measurement.
 One way to do that is to construct an identity operator using these eignkets
 and then simply multiply it with the state in question.
 The result would be a superposition of eigenkets as we wanted.
 Then the amplitudes will tell us with what probability we get which eigenket,
 thus which eigenvalue as the measurement outcome.
 Nothing new or subtle yet.
 But here's the issue.
 Consider the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as defined yesterday.
 Now if it is true, as has been shown, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{L}d\tilde{x}\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle \left\langle \tilde{x}\right|=1$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle =\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then it seems that the only outcome of measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on any arbitrary state, must result in the value 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

.
 However, we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists$
\end_inset

 states s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =-\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 has been explicitly defined earlier.
 It's measurement must yield a 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 So what's wrong?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The obvious thing to try would be to see what we get when we do 
\begin_inset Formula $1.\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{L}d\tilde{y}\left|\tilde{y}\right\rangle \left\langle \tilde{y}\right|\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If one uses the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \tilde{y}|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 (well this itself is a little tricky, works well only if you define it
 as a partial sum first and then take the limits), then apparently 
\begin_inset Formula $1.\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 which is bizzare.
 And if one uses the expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 then by the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $1.\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as expected, but then (fine i'll have to do the calculation to find what
 is the issue in that case) the expansion we get is something like this
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}\left(-1\right)^{m}\left|x=\tilde{x}+mL\right\rangle =\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Here's the important step.
 
\begin_inset Formula $1.\left|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle =\sum_{n,m}\int d\tilde{y}\left\langle x=\tilde{y}+mL|x=\tilde{x}+nL\right\rangle \left|x=\tilde{y}+mL\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If I don't expand out 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{y}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, then the only operation I can perform to proceed is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \tilde{y}|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 which is unambiguously zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}\neq\tilde{y}$
\end_inset

.
 So then the only question that remains is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \tilde{x}|\tilde{x}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which we said is zero only when treated as a partial sum.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\strikeout on
This maybe rationalized by imagining that 
\begin_inset Formula $1.\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle =\sum_{m}\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 which is basically just a consequence of the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\tilde{x}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is not normalized to even start with!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thought: It maybe more helpful to think of measuring the modular variable
 as extracting only the modular part, instead of thinking of it as displacements
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Basically, even 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|p\right\rangle $
\end_inset

s are eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left|p\right\rangle =\cos(pL/\hbar)\left|p\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|p\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are also complete and well behaved relatively anyway.
 So how must then I use this? [I must eventually figure out the equivalence
 between these but first I must get some reasonable answers].
 Infact I am not even sure which set of eigenstates should one use for such
 purposes.
 In anycase, proceeding with this, let's see what we get.
 Looks like I need to know for sure exactly how to convert between position
 and momentum space.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As it turns out, there's a paper titled `Nonlocal Young Tests with EPR correlate
d particles' which states ``The position measurements at the detection screens
 may thus be viewed as effective momentum measurements on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{T}'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

''.
 This was again after a discussion with Ali
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Discussion with Ali
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I explained to him the issues, well the paradox stated above (there are
 mistakes in the results there, scaling).
 Obviously things looked spooky.
 I told him why I thought that a measurement on the screen shouldn't work
 (
\begin_inset Formula $[x,p_{mod}]\neq0$
\end_inset

) and was trying to construct the right set of eigenstates etc.
 He however he insisted I must extract this information off of the screen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He explained the idea of how he used coupling with spin to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma\otimes\sigma\right\rangle =\frac{1}{4}\left\langle D\otimes D\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as a way of measuring the correlated expectation value of the system (in
 his contextuality paper).
 Point being twofold (he didn't say it explicitly like this, but he has
 some crazy good intuition)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Recall that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=\psi_{1}+e^{i\phi}\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

, when you evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{*}\psi$
\end_inset

 it doesn't depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 if observed when 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 don't overlap.
 However the modular momentum does at that time.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 dependence re-emerges when 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 overlap finally.
 The point is that the information you thought you can't get from the screen,
 you can.
 Somehow the modular momentum information is contained in the position measureme
nt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Next, note that for a product state like 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle +e^{i\phi}\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, you won't see interference on the screen of either observers.
 This is because you're left with a mixed state, after you trace out the
 other system.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{1}\right|+\left|\psi_{2}\right\rangle \left\langle \psi_{2}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 If you however calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x,y)=\psi(x,y)^{*}\psi(x,y)$
\end_inset

, you'll see the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 dependence re-emerges, depending on again, the overlap condition.
 So basically, the modular variable expectation you evaluated, which depended
 on this 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle X\otimes U^{\dagger}XU\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 should be in some form present in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 correlation.
 This is what you have to extract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Remark: It maybe mentioned that it is important to get the scaling factors
 right between this expectation and expectation of the modular variables,
 because that is crucial for the violation, if we intent to measure the
 modular variables indirectly.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
He again showed me the Non local young experiment with the EPR state.
 That actually has implemented recovery of modular variables in some way
 which is worth looking at.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
He also enquired if I evaluated the commutation: 
\begin_inset Formula $[U_{1}^{\dagger}XU_{1},U_{2}^{\dagger}XU_{2}]$
\end_inset

, which I should and add to the report.
 Tomorrow.
 
\end_layout

