 waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For photons, multiple issues: There's no schrodinger equation (
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}/2m$
\end_inset

 doesn't exist, its non-relatavistic, but you could put in the actual relativist
ic hamiltonian, but that has issues by itself).
 Then there's nowhere we quantize 
\begin_inset Formula $q,p$
\end_inset

, we only quantize 
\begin_inset Formula $E,B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Read about 35 pages from the quantum optics book by Scully.
 It explained interesting things.
 Here's an email I wrote to Ali after reading that.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I wasnt able to rest properly because my mind kept thinking about the free
 evolution problem.
 I re-derived the result for matter waves, but the issue is that I am able
 to arrive at that result without even having to assume the grating.
 So obviously Im missing something.
 In addition, I was thinking about whether or not I can even extend that
 result for photons, but the issue is that with photons, we dont quantize
 its momentum and position.
 I therefore cant quite use momentum as a generator of translations by
 assuming the usual commutations.
 To verify my reasoning, I started to read the more advanced book on quantum
 optics by Scully and Zubairy.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

On page 25 it states Thus it is natural to ask what are the 
\backslash
phis for photons? Strictly speaking therere no such wave functions! One
 may not speak of particles in a radiation field in the same sense as in
 the elementary quantum mechanics of systems of particles used in the last
 chapter.
 The reason is that the wave equation..
 solutions of Schrodingers time dependent wave function corresponding to
 an energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 have a circular frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\lambda}=+E_{\lambda}/\hbar$
\end_inset

, while the monochromatic solutions of the wave equation have both 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\omega_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The E and B fields satisfying the Maxwell equations in free space, and
 therefore satisfying the wave equation too, are real and are not eigenfunctions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $i\hbar\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

.
 A Schrodinger wave of given energy must be complex.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

He goes on to say that the concept of a photon wave function must be used
 with care and can be very misleading.
 However as we shall see, each of the above objections to the concept can
 be overcome, where he is referring to issues pointed out by Bohm in his
 classic Quantum Theory book.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I think the best option is for me to continue reading the book to understand
 this notion better.
 In anycase, I think tomorrow, we should talk to Ottfried about the progress
 weve made so far and ask him about this.
 Im sure hed know this very well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Basically the issue is that for massive objects, classically we have newtonian
 that gives particle, qm gives waves.
 For photons, classically we have waves, qft gives (both waves and) particles.
 So to compare, you must elevate both to a field description and then figure
 the meaning of a wavefunction.
 It's quite nicely given in the text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wasn't sure about which journal to publish in between the new journal of
 physics and PRA.
 [later: I think I'll stick with PRA for the moment, especially becaues
 of the following.
 Two great researchers, one has money one doesn't.
 So NJP is out of the question for the one without money.
 I'd rather publish in a place where you don't have to be rich just to publish.]
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Progress
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
