\begin_layout Itemize
Commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $[U^{\dagger}XU,U^{\dagger}XU]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Ali had an idea about using the Heisenberg equation to get 
\begin_inset Formula $dX/dt$
\end_inset

 and then using that to get 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\dagger}XU$
\end_inset

 explicitly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[
\emph on
new
\emph default
] That idea didn't help much, but I figured I could explicitly evaluate
 these by simply using 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dx\left|x\right\rangle \left\langle x\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Using this and while discussing with Ali, I realized that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Z^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, so essentially the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be expanded as some 
\begin_inset Formula $iZ\sin$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $ZX=-XZ$
\end_inset

 follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(x+L)=Z(x-L)=-Z(x)$
\end_inset

.
 This is very elegent!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So then 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\dagger}(\theta)XU(\theta)=XU(2\theta)$
\end_inset

 and I can even expand 
\begin_inset Formula $U(2\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 So that helps alot.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I also realized the mistake I was making.
 Just because 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{iA}e^{iB}=-e^{iB}e^{iA}$
\end_inset

 doesn't mean 
\begin_inset Formula $AB=-BA$
\end_inset

.
 I know I'm that stupid [besides if you try to take log, then addition doesn't
 remain commutative as pointed out in the GHZ paper].
 I assumed something intuitively using the spin case (which was correct),
 couldn't prove it was correct so assumed this as a correction and got into
 issues.
 So everything is consistent.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
