\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Evaluated the explicit commutations for all 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Z,Y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=ZX$
\end_inset

 (or some such).
 It was fun.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}\neq1$
\end_inset

, things didn't work perfectly! But that's good, else I would've obtained
 a answers identical to the usual case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also evaluated the commutation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $[UXU,UXU]$
\end_inset

 explicitly (need to verify it, will do so tomorrow/or on Monday)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[
\emph on
new
\emph default
] Realized that the most elegent way would be to use 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}=e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=e^{i\hat{x}2\pi/2L}$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=\hat{X}\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

 or some such.
 So what justification do I have for using this funky 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

? The answer to that is that I want to allow the wavefunctions to be physical
 (don't want to use a countable superposition of position eigenkets).
 One neat way around it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=Z(\hat{x}_{mod2L})$
\end_inset

.
 This just works beautifully.
 So I get to have my cake and eat it too!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I want to think about it a little deeper at some point (because it looks
 like the GHZ case where they extract only one bit of information).
 I'm sure there's more to it but not clear yet.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 I don't change because it displaces position.
 So the justfication is that I am treating position in a special way in
 my setup, therefore the operators are such.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Perhaps the EPR would need the conventional 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{mod}$
\end_inset

.
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[
\emph on
new
\emph default
] Also figured that perhaps instead of making histograms, I can simply evaluate
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(pL/\hbar)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Just realized that the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 polarizer is not infact supposed to do 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H\right\rangle \to\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}},\left|V\right\rangle \to\frac{\left|H\right\rangle -\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 That's wrong.
 It basically sends both to the same state, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H\right\rangle \to\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}},\left|V\right\rangle \to\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 (except the normalization of course).
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H\right\rangle \propto\left|H'\right\rangle +\left|V'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|V\right\rangle \propto\left|H'\right\rangle -\left|V'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 polarizer is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H'\right\rangle \left\langle H'\right|$
\end_inset

, so that wipes out the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|V'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Now it makes perfect sense.
 The good thing is that my result is correct regardless because I project
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H\right\rangle \left\langle H\right|$
\end_inset

 in the end, but anyway.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
