\begin_layout Subsection
Tuesday, July 7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Work
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
GHZ
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Figured that in the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit, one can easily construct the corresponding continuous variable case
 for the GHZ.
 If one assumes a cylindrical space, then also this can be done (just impose
 periodic boundary conditions on the wavefunction).
 What must be interesting is the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\ne\infty$
\end_inset

 case.
 In this case, I must be able to show something like you get some values
 (continuous) but according to local realism, some other measurement must
 give, say the product, of these, but it doesn't happen in experiments (as
 predicted by QM).
 The trouble is that I must have an eigenstate, else repeated measurements
 won't work.
 The moment I enforce an eigenstate, I won't get a continuous valued outcome,
 I'll get exactly one number.
 To keep both aspects, I must come up with something different.
 Question is what? What are some of my guiding principles? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is it even possible to have an eigenstate of an operator and not know the
 outcome of measurement? Not that I know of
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

So I must construct some sort of eigenstates, such that the operation yields
 a continuous valued, but fixed outcome, depending on the state
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Then I must use some anti-commutation etc.
 like relation between these operators and measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But the whole idea of an eigenstate is troublesome in our formalism.
 So what makes GHZ really remarkable? The outcome predicted is in contradiction
 with classical expections (so far bell test also works the same), and you
 don't need to repeat the experiment many times (and bell needs the experiment
 to be repeated).
 So I must come up with something in which you make a single measurement,
 with neither of the measurement outcomes certain, but I must have some
 sort of classical constraint on the measurement (by assuming local hidden
 variables) and then show that quantum mechanically it fails, with a single
 (or a given number M) measurement (meaning all Alice, Bob, Clausius).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I can't quite think of anything just yet.
 So one way to proceed is to understand what goes wrong with the finite
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 case and then see if there's something I can do to fix it.
 Bascially there, ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So it's useless basically | discussed with Ali also
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
