\begin_layout Subsection
Monday, July 13
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Otfried's lecture
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
He talked about the PBR argument, pretty damn awesome, especially given
 that its so recent and that its so simple (I could've thought of it, just
 proves that I must keep pushing the limits)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Work/Draft
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
I should simply plot 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p_{1},p_{2}|\Psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x_{1},x_{2}|\Psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 since the former will show what kind of resolution is needed.
 Did that, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:psiP"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So now if I want to resolve this, I must have the ball park 
\begin_inset Formula $p=h/L=p_{z}x/D$
\end_inset

.
 So from this I get that the typical distance on the screen must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda D/L=x$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $D\gg L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 will be of usable units.
 The resolution should be then about 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{10}^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h/L$
\end_inset

.
 The range as is clear from the figure, should be about 
\begin_inset Formula $6h/L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle p_{1}p_{2}|\varphi\right\rangle \right|$
\end_inset

 part has been ignored because it is expected to be roughly constant over
 
\begin_inset Formula $6h/L$
\end_inset

.
 This is because we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\ll D$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the slit size and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 the separation between centres of consecutive slits.
 This can be confirmed from the fact that in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:psiP"

\end_inset

, both the fourier transform and the analytic solution divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle p_{1}p_{2}|\varphi\right\rangle \right|$
\end_inset

, are qualitatively the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that this was done only for illustration of what we get on the screen.
 The theoretical results are exact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Played a little more with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x_{1}x_{2}|\Psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and found that the phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 essentially just introduces a nearly identical mirror in the imaginary
 part of the wavefunction.
 You analtyically have 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{2}\left(i\sin(\delta')\left[\left|++\right\rangle -\left|--\right\rangle \right]+\cos(\delta')\left[\left|+-\right\rangle -\left|-+\right\rangle \right]\right)$
\end_inset

 which automatically means what I said.
 Quite nice.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Also figured that this can be easily translated to the theory of diffraction
 in 2 dimensions.
 Therefore the patterns looked familiar (for say 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In that setting, creating any aribtrary entangled state is straight forward;
 the drawback is you can't do the bell test etc.
 since it's a single particle system now.
 I think this is interesting, but we'll not pursue it for the moment
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Git - now Ali is also using git, it has become a lot more easier to work
 in collaboration.
 The online thing didn't have enough resolution
\end_layout

